replies.bodyText:
I'm not quite sure what "cross-qualifiers" means but you can do Arc.container().select(MongoClient.class, Any.Literal.INSTANCE) to obtain all beans that satisfy the MongoClient required type no matter what other qualifiers are defined. But then in order to be able to access the qualifiers for each bean instance you would have to iterate over the instance handles, i.e. something like:
for (InstanceHandle<MongoClient> handle : Arc.container().select(MongoClient.class, Any.Literal.INSTANCE).handles()) {
     String clientName = getMongoClientName(handle.getBean());
     .... // I'm not sure about the bean.getName() part?
     clients.put(clientName == null ? "default" : clientName, handle.get());
}
In any case, the (MongoClient) Arc.container().instance(bean.getName()).get() part does not seem to be very safe...

@mkouba If I remember correctly when there is multiple beans of the same type, only one can have no name (so `bean.getName() return null) and the other will have a name. At least for MongoDB this is how we create them (at least when we created the health check).
This is also how it is done on the Datasource extension (OK, both are my impl so it's normal): https://github.com/quarkusio/quarkus/blob/master/extensions/agroal/runtime/src/main/java/io/quarkus/agroal/runtime/health/DataSourceHealthCheck.java#L28
If we change it here, we may change it in all extensions that have such health checks.

